                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p rend=\"align(right)\"><date>Tuesday, Rosh Hodesh Sivan(May), 1863</date>.</p>\n            <p>Peace and all that is good, forever:</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">If some cure were found for my weak nerves, my low<lb/> spirits, and\n                for my bitter feelings, it would be a letter from you,<lb/> you, an appointed\n                officer and honored in your place. But when you<lb/> begin to complain even more\n                what shall I say ? Unfortunately,<lb/> you have no insight.</p>\n            <p rend=\"indent(1)\">I am very grateful to you for your frankness when you<lb/> say that\n                    <persName>Pappe</persName> is my friend. I did not expect anything else.\n                Not<lb/> because of my mitzvoth, nor because of my situation, but a learned<lb/> man\n                like me is revolted by such pseudo-learning. Unfortunately,<lb/> this type of\n                    <sic>Cnazan</sic> constitutes the majority of conservative Ju-<lb/>daism.\n                Orthodoxy is an artificial, a Jesuitical thing. I am<lb/> proud to say that I spurn\n                orthodoxy, for I want the true Judaism,<lb/> such as our sages have received and\n                transmitted through the Oral<lb/> Law, and such as our children should receive, as I\n                said last <date>Sun-<lb/>day</date> at a meeting for the establishment of a Sunday\n                school. You<lb/> must admit that through the work of such people, who do nothing\n                for<lb/> the education of the children, must have as a result that Judaism<lb/> will\n                die with us. Will <persName>Pappe's</persName> children know anything about a\n                Tal-<lb/>mud? Will they know what the mitzvoth from the Torah are? Or<lb/> mitzvoth\n                of the rabbis? Is it not a great, brazenness on the part<lb/> of <sic>sucha</sic>\n                man to rely purely upon customs and to stick his head be-<lb/>tween hills and\n                mountains while the learned and righteous people<lb/> of the world in\n                    <placeName>Germany</placeName> are astonished at my work? Does he\n                under-<lb/>stand anything, even with regard to ordinary meanings of the Talmud,<lb/>\n                the Mishnah, idol-worship? Yes, I consider myself among those<lb/> about whom our\n                sages, may their memory be for a blessing, said, “All<lb/> that a good student is\n                destined to being forth as a novelty, etc.” I<lb/> insist upon holding on to the\n                old, but in order to save something<lb/> from the shipwreck which may at all\n                possibly be saved, I shall, if</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p32z1392w/canvas/p1"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
